# Blueprint 📐

Use the `struct` keyword.

```c
struct Student {
    char name[50];
    int age;
    float gpa;
};
```

**Declaring Variables:**
```c
struct Student s1, s2;
```
Here `s1` and `s2` are variables of type `struct Student`.

# The Dot Operator ⏺️

Use the dot `.` operator to access or modify members.

```c
// Initialization
s1.age = 20;
s1.gpa = 3.8;
strcpy(s1.name, "Alice");

// Accessing
printf("%s is %d years old.", s1.name, s1.age);
```

You can also initialize all at once:
```c
struct Student s1 = {"Alice", 20, 3.8};
```

# A Class of Students 🏫

You can create arrays of structures just like arrays of integers.

```c
struct Student class[30];
// class[0] is the first student
// class[1] is the second student

class[0].age = 19;
printf("First student: %s", class[0].name);
```

# The Arrow Operator 🏹

When you have a pointer to a structure, accessing members is different.

```c
struct Student s1 = {"Bob", 21, 3.5};
struct Student *ptr = &s1;

// Standard way (clunky)
(*ptr).age = 22;

// Arrow Operator (Preferred)
ptr->age = 22;
```
So, `ptr->age` is the same as `(*ptr).age`.

# Creating Aliases 🏷️

`typedef` gives a new name to an existing type. It makes code cleaner.

```c
// Old way
struct Point {
    int x, y;
};
struct Point p1;

// With typedef
typedef struct {
    int x, y;
} Point;

Point p1; // No need to write 'struct' anymore!
```

# Shared Space: Unions 🤝

Like a structure, but all members **share the same memory location**.
The size of the union is the size of its largest member.

```c
union Data {
    int i;
    float f;
    char str[20];
};
```

**Key Difference:**
- In `struct`, `i`, `f`, and `str` exist simultaneously.
- In `union`, only **one** member can hold a value at a time. Writing to `f` overwrites `i`.

# Named Constants 🔢

For defining a variable that can hold only a specific set of values.

```c
enum Day {SUNDAY, MONDAY, TUESDAY, WEDNESDAY, THURSDAY, FRIDAY, SATURDAY};

enum Day today = WEDNESDAY;

if (today == SUNDAY) {
    printf("Time to relax!");
}
```
Internally, `SUNDAY` is 0, `MONDAY` is 1, etc.

